# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-dart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-dart/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:dodge-dart/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:dodge-dart/adanero] Adanero was granted the privilege of town (*villa*) in 1630, during the reign of Philip IV, becoming independent from the land of Ávila.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] When Spain was still an autocratic regime, he was appointed prime minister by King Juan Carlos in 1976.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] At the time of his appointment, he was not a well-known figure, making many political forces skeptical of his government.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] However, he oversaw the end of the Francoist Cortes, and the legalisation of all political parties (including the Communist Party of Spain, a particularly difficult move).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He led the Union of the Democratic Centre and won the 1977 general election.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1981, he resigned and founded the party Democratic and Social Centre (CDS), which was elected to the Cortes numerous times.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He retired from politics in 1991 and from public life in 2003, due to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Adolfo Suárez González was born on 25 September 1932 in Cebreros in the Province of Ávila of Spain, the eldest son of Hipólito Suárez Guerra, a lawyer, and Herminia González Prados.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Both of his parents supported the Republicans during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] At the age of 18, Suárez was president of the Ávila chapter of Catholic Action.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He studied law at the University of Salamanca, after which he took a job at the municipal government of Ávila in 1955.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He subsequently became a member of Opus Dei, and obtained a doctorate at the Central University of Madrid.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He also worked briefly as a porter at Madrid's Atocha railway station.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1958, Suárez became the personal secretary of Fernando Herrero Tejedor, the newly appointed civil governor of Ávila.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] When Tejedor was made deputy secretary-general of the *Movimiento Nacional* in 1961, Suárez became his *chef de cabinet*.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He gradually rose through the ranks of the *Movimiento*.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1965, Suárez was appointed programme director of the state broadcaster Radio y Televisión Española (RTVE).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1967, he was elected to the Francoist Cortes.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1968, Suárez was promoted to civil governor and provincial head of the *Movimiento* in Segovia.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1969, he was made director general of RTVE.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Under this capacity, he became a close friend to future king Prince Juan Carlos.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In March 1975, Herrero Tejedor became secretary-general of the *Movimiento* while Suárez was appointed deputy secretary-general.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Herrero Tejedor was considered a likely candidate for prime minister until his death in a car accident in June.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In December, shortly after Francisco Franco's death, Suárez was promoted to secretary-general by prime minister Carlos Arias Navarro, and became a member of Arias's cabinet.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In the same year, he also became a founding member of the Spanish People's Union (*Unión del Pueblo Español*, UDPE).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In July 1976, King Juan Carlos requested the resignation of Arias.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The relatively obscure Suárez was chosen as the new Prime Minister of Spain, surprising many observers.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] At the age of 43, he was Spain's youngest prime minister in the 20th century.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Due to his Francoist ties, Suárez enjoyed the trust of the political right, while the reformists were dismayed by his appointment.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Nevertheless, it was noted that due to his age (he turned 7 years old the year that the civil war ended), Suárez was not as strongly associated with the bloody Civil War or the most brutal years of Franco's rule as the older politicians.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Within a year of his appointment, Suárez had rapidly introduced reform measures and taken decisive steps in Spain's transition to democracy (*La Transición*).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The Political Reform Act, which permitted universal suffrage and established the basis for a new, bicameral parliament, was passed by a huge majority in the Francoist Cortes in November 1976 and overwhelmingly approved by a referendum in December.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez managed to placate the conservative military officers, while also reaching out to Felipe González's Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) and later, Santiago Carrillo's Communist Party of Spain (PCE).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Between February and April 1977, the PSOE and the PCE were both legalised, trade unions were recognised, and the *Movimiento* was abolished.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The legalisation of the PCE in particular provoked fury in the Spanish military; Suárez responded by sacking hardliners and promoting more liberal officers such as Manuel Gutiérrez Mellado.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] On 15 June, Suárez led the Union of the Democratic Centre (*Unión de Centro Democrático*, UCD) to victory in Spain's first free elections in 41 years, and became the first democratically elected prime minister of the post-Francoist Spain.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 1978, during Suárez's premiership, Spain voted in the United Nations General Assembly condemning human rights abuses in Chile, thus distancing Spain from the Francoist-influenced military dictatorship of Augusto Pinochet.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's centrist government instituted further democratic reforms.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] A new constitution, which recognised Spain as a constitutional monarchy, was approved by a referendum in December 1978.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In an effort to address separatist tensions and calls for increased local autonomy, Suárez also negotiated the creation of Spain's autonomous communities.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's coalition won the 1979 Spanish general election under the new constitution.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's political power eroded as he struggled to deal with economic recession, mounting violent activity by ETA, calls for further regional autonomy and divisions within his own party.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He became increasingly withdrawn from governance, partly due to a chronic dental condition.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He survived a motion of no confidence presented by Felipe González and the PSOE in May 1980.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In January 1981, trailing in the polls behind the PSOE and faced with a revolt within the UCD, Suárez announced his resignation as prime minister.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] A month later, as parliament took the vote to confirm Suárez's successor Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo, Lieutenant-Colonel Antonio Tejero and around 200 Civil Guards stormed the chamber in an attempted coup and held the lawmakers hostage for some 22 hours.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez, along with two other parliamentarians, exhibited defiance by remaining calmly seated during the panic.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The 23-F coup attempt ("El Tejerazo") failed as it was opposed by Spain's main newspaper El País (who managed to get a special edition in favor of the constitution issued and distributed on the evening of the coup attempt) and denounced by King Juan Carlos I in a televised address.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Meanwhile, promised military support for the coup failed to materialise – with few exceptions, most notably Jaime Milans del Bosch who led pro-coup troops in Valencia.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He retired from active politics in 1991, for personal reasons.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez was awarded the *Príncipe de Asturias a la Concordia* in September 1996 for his role in Spain's early democracy.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] On 8 June 2007, during the celebration of the 30th anniversary of the first democratic elections, King Juan Carlos appointed Suárez the 1,193rd Knight of the Order of the Golden Fleece.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] He was also a member of the Club de Madrid, an independent organization (based in Madrid) that is composed of more than 80 former democratic Prime Ministers and Presidents.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The group works to strengthen democratic governance and leadership.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] On 31 May 2005, Suárez's son, Adolfo Suárez Illana, announced on Spanish television that his father was suffering from Alzheimer's disease.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] The announcement followed speculation about Suárez's health in the Spanish media.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] On 21 March 2014, his son announced that his death from neurological deterioration was imminent.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez then died as a result of a respiratory infection on 23 March 2014 in a clinic in Madrid.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suarez was given a state funeral and was buried in the cloister of Ávila Cathedral.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] On 26 March 2014, the Spanish government decided to rename the Madrid-Barajas Airport to Adolfo Suárez Madrid–Barajas Airport in honour of his service to the country.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In December 2025 a woman accused Suárez of sexual abuse between 1982–1985, beginning when she was seventeen and still a minor, and Suárez was about fifty.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] However, no criminal proceedings are expected to take place due to Suárez's death in 2014 and an expiration of the alleged crimes.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's secretary reportedly disputed the accusations made against her former employer.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez married María del Amparo Illana Elórtegui in 1961.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Their eldest daughter, María del Amparo ("Mariam") Suárez Illana (1962–2004), died of breast cancer on 6 March 2004, following an 11-year illness.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Both of her younger sisters also suffered from the same illness.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] She was the mother of two children, Alejandra Romero Suárez (born 1990), herself the current holder of her grandfather's dukedom, and Fernando Romero Suárez (born 1993).
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suarez' youngest daughter, María Sonsoles Suárez Illana (born 1967), became a TV news anchor for Antena 3.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] From 1992 to 1994 she was married to José María Martínez-Bordiú y Bassó de Roviralta (a nephew of Cristóbal Martínez-Bordiú, the son-in-law of Francisco Franco); the couple was without issue.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] In 2012 she married the Mozambican musician Paulo Wilson, and they separated in 2017.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's eldest son, Adolfo Suárez Illana, is a politician and lawyer who is heavily involved with the world of bullfighting; he has two sons.
[src:dodge-dart/adolfo-suárez] Suárez had two more children, his daughter Laura and his son Francisco Javier; both remain unmarried.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:dodge-dart/alternator-auto] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The color **amber** is a pure chroma color, located on the color wheel midway between the colors of yellow and orange.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The color name is derived from the material also known as amber, which is commonly found in a range of yellow-orange-brown-red colors; likewise, as a color, *amber* can refer to a range of yellow-orange colors.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] In English, the first recorded use of the term as a color name, rather than a reference to the specific substance, was in 1500.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] Amber is one of several technically defined colors used in automotive signal lamps.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] In North America, SAE standard J578 governs the colorimetry of vehicle lights, while outside North America the internationalized European ECE regulations hold force.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] Both standards designate a range of orange-yellow hues in the CIE color space as "amber".
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] In the past, the ECE amber definition was more restrictive than the SAE definition, but the current ECE definition is identical to the more permissive SAE standard.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The SAE formally uses the term "yellow amber", though the color is most often referred to as "yellow".
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] This is not the same as selective yellow, a color used in some fog lamps and headlamps.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The entirety of these definitions lie outside the gamut of the sRGB color space — such a pure color cannot be represented using RGB primaries.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The color box shown above is a desaturated approximation, produced by taking the centroid of the standard definition and moving it towards the D65 white point, until it meets the sRGB gamut triangle.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] The color temperature of LED lamps is called amber when their wavelengths are about 590 nm.
[src:dodge-dart/amber-color] Chronomatic low-pressure sodium-vapor lamps emit light ranging from 580 to 590 nm.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] An **ambulance** is a medically equipped vehicle used to transport patients to treatment facilities, such as hospitals.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Typically, out-of-hospital medical care is provided to the patient during the transport.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances are used to respond to medical emergencies by emergency medical services (EMS), and can rapidly transport paramedics and other first responders, carry equipment for administering emergency care, and transport patients to hospital or other definitive care.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Most ambulances use a design based on vans or pickup trucks, though others take the form of motorcycles, buses, hearses, aircraft and boats.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances are generally considered emergency vehicles authorized to be equipped with emergency lights and sirens.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Generally, vehicles count as an ambulance if they can transport patients.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] However, it varies by jurisdiction as to whether a non-emergency patient transport vehicle (also called an ambulette) is counted as an ambulance.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These vehicles are not usually (although there are exceptions) equipped with life-support equipment, and are usually crewed by staff with fewer qualifications than the crew of emergency ambulances.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Conversely, EMS agencies may also have nontransporting EMS vehicles that cannot transport patients.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The term *ambulance* comes from the Latin word *ambulare* as meaning 'to walk or move about' which is a reference to early medical care where patients were moved by lifting or wheeling.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The word originally meant a moving hospital, which follows an army in its movements.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances (*ambulancias* in Spanish) were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish forces during the siege of Málaga by the Catholic Monarchs against the Emirate of Granada.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] During the American Civil War vehicles for conveying the wounded off the field of battle were called ambulance wagons.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Field hospitals were still called ambulances during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870 and in the Serbo-Turkish war of 1876 even though the wagons were first referred to as ambulances about 1854 during the Crimean War.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The history of the ambulance begins in ancient times, with the use of carts to transport incurable patients by force.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish, and civilian variants were put into operation during the 1830s.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Advances in technology throughout the 19th and 20th centuries led to modern self-powered ambulances.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances can be grouped into types depending on whether or not they transport patients, and under what conditions.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulance design must take into account local conditions and infrastructure.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Maintained roads are necessary for road-going ambulances to arrive on scene and then transport the patient to a hospital, though in rugged areas four-wheel drive or all-terrain vehicles can be used.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Fuel must be available and service facilities are necessary to maintain the vehicle.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Methods of summoning (e.g. telephone) and dispatching ambulances usually rely on electronic equipment, which itself often relies on an intact power grid.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances often have two stages of manufacturing.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The first is frequently the manufacture of light or medium truck chassis-cabs or full-size vans (or in some places, cars) such as Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, Toyota, or Ford.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The second manufacturer (known as second stage manufacturer) modifies the vehicle (which is sometimes purchased incomplete, having no body or interior behind the driver's seat) and turns it into an ambulance by adding bodywork, emergency vehicle equipment, and interior fittings.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This is done by one of two methods – either coachbuilding, where the modifications are started from scratch and built on to the vehicle, or using a modular system, where a pre-built 'box' is put on to the empty chassis of the ambulance, and then finished off.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Modern ambulances are typically powered by internal combustion engines, which can be powered by any conventional fuel, including diesel, gasoline or liquefied petroleum gas, depending on the preference of the operator and the availability of different options.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] As electric vehicles become more common ambulances are moving to electricity and can even be solar-powered with solar photovoltaic modules integrated into the rooftops.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Colder regions often use gasoline-powered engines, as diesels can be difficult to start when they are cold.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Warmer regions may favor diesel engines, as they are more efficient and more durable.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Diesel power is sometimes chosen due to safety concerns, after a series of fires involving gasoline-powered ambulances during the 1980s.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These fires were ultimately attributed in part to gasoline's higher volatility in comparison to diesel fuel.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The type of engine may be determined by the manufacturer: in the past two decades, Ford would only sell vehicles for ambulance conversion if they are diesel-powered.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Beginning in 2010, Ford will sell its ambulance chassis with a gasoline engine in order to meet emissions requirements.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service has set a target for all ambulances to be fully electric as part of the Net Zero campaign by 2045.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Many regions have prescribed standards which ambulances should, or must, meet in order to be used for their role.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These standards may have different levels which reflect the type of patient which the ambulance is expected to transport (for instance specifying a different standard for routine patient transport than high dependency), or may base standards on the size of vehicle.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] For instance, in Europe, the European Committee for Standardization publishes the standard CEN 1789, which specifies minimum compliance levels across the build of ambulance, including crash resistance, equipment levels, and exterior marking.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In the United States, standards for ambulance design have existed since 1976, where the standard is published by the General Services Administration and known as KKK-A-1822.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This standard has been revised several times, and is currently in version 'F' change notice #13, known as KKK-A-1822F.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The National Fire Protection Association has also published a design standard, NFPA 1917, which offers an alternative to KKK-A-1822F.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The Commission on Accreditation of Ambulance Services (CAAS) has published its Ground Vehicle Standard for Ambulances v2.0, effective July 2019.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This standard is similar to the KKK-A-1822F and NFPA 1917–2019 specifications.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The decision on which of the current (3) standards to require is left up to each individual state legislature or EMS director.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Some states have no specific requirement, while others specify which standard is acceptable.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Others, yet, allow the end user to decide which standard to comply to.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In the United States and Canada, there are four types of ambulances: Type I, Type II, Type III, and Type IV.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Type I is based on a heavy truck chassis-cab with a custom rear compartment that is often referred to as a "box" or "module", primarily used for Advanced Life Support (ALS) or Mobile Intensive Care Unit (MICU), as well as rescue work.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Type II is based on a commercial heavy-duty van with few modifications except for a raised roof and a secondary air conditioning unit for the rear of the vehicle, primarily used for Basic Life Support (BLS) and transfer of patients, though they are occasionally also used for ALS and rescue.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Type III is a van chassis-cab with a custom-made rear compartment, used for ALS and rescue.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Type IV is for *ad hoc* patient transfer using smaller utility vehicles selected for maneuverability in special environments such as dense crowds at events; these are uncommon and are not subject to federal regulations in the United States.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The move towards standardisation is now reaching countries without a history of prescriptive codes, such as India, which approved its first national standard for ambulance construction in 2013.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances, like other emergency vehicles, are required to operate in most weather conditions, including those during which civilian drivers often elect to stay off the road.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Also, the ambulance crew's responsibilities to their patient often preclude their use of safety devices such as seat belts.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Research has shown that ambulances are more likely to be involved in motor vehicle collisions resulting in injury or death than either fire trucks or police cars.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Unrestrained occupants, particularly those riding in the patient-care compartment, are particularly vulnerable.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] When compared to civilian vehicles of similar size, one study found that on a per-accident basis, ambulance collisions tend to involve more people, and result in more injuries.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] An 11-year retrospective study concluded in 2001 found that although most fatal ambulance crashes in the United States occurred during emergency runs, they typically occurred on improved, straight, dry roads, during clear weather.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Furthermore, paramedics are also at risk in ambulances while helping patients, as 27 paramedics died during ambulance trips in the US between 1991 and 2006.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In addition to the equipment directly used for the treatment of patients, ambulances may be fitted with a range of additional equipment which is used in order to facilitate patient care.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In parts of the world that lack a high level of infrastructure, ambulances are designed to meet local conditions, being built using intermediate technology.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances can also be trailers, which are pulled by bicycles, motorcycles, tractors, or animals.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Animal-powered ambulances can be particularly useful in regions that are subject to flooding.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Motorcycles fitted with sidecars (or motorcycle ambulances) are also used, though they are subject to some of the same limitations as more traditional over-the-road ambulances.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The level of care provided by these ambulances varies between merely providing transport to a medical clinic to providing on-scene and continuing care during transport.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The design of intermediate technology ambulances must take into account not only the operation and maintenance of the ambulance, but its construction as well.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The robustness of the design becomes more important, as does the nature of the skills required to properly operate the vehicle.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Cost-effectiveness can be a high priority.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Emergency ambulances are highly likely to be involved in hazardous situations, including incidents such as a road traffic collision, as these emergencies create people who are likely to be in need of treatment.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] They are required to gain access to patients as quickly as possible, and in many countries, are given dispensation from obeying certain traffic laws.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] For instance, they may be able to run the red light or stop sign , or be permitted to break the speed limit.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Generally, the priority of the response to the call will be assigned by the dispatcher, but the priority of the return will be decided by the ambulance crew based on the severity of the patient's illness or injury.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Passive visual warnings are usually part of the design of the vehicle, and involve the use of high contrast patterns.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Older ambulances (and those in developing countries) are more likely to have their pattern painted on, whereas modern ambulances generally carry retro-reflective designs, which reflects light from car headlights or torches.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In addition to retro-reflective markings, some services now have the vehicles painted in a bright (sometimes fluorescent) yellow or orange for maximum visual impact, though classic white or red are also common.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Fire department-operated ambulances are often painted red to match the fire apparatuses.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Another passive marking form is the word *ambulance* (or local language variant) spelled out in reverse on the front of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This enables drivers of other vehicles to more easily identify an approaching ambulance in their rear view mirrors.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances may display the name of their owner or operator, and an emergency telephone number for the ambulance service.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances may also carry an emblem (either as part of the passive warning markings or not), such as a Red Cross, Red Crescent or Red Crystal (collective known as the Protective Symbols).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These are symbols laid down by the Geneva Convention, and all countries signatory to it agree to restrict their use to either (1) Military Ambulances or (2) the national Red Cross or Red Crescent society.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Use by any other person, organization or agency is in breach of international law.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The protective symbols are designed to indicate to all people (especially combatants in the case of war) that the vehicle is neutral and is not to be fired upon, hence giving protection to the medics and their casualties, although this has not always been adhered to.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In Israel, Magen David Adom, the Red Cross member organization use a red Star of David, but this does not have recognition beyond Israeli borders, where they must use the Red Crystal.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The Star of Life is widely used, and was originally designed and governed by the U.S.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, because the Red Cross symbol is legally protected by both National and international law.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulance services with historical origins such as the Order of St John, the Order of Malta Ambulance Corps and Malteser International often use the Maltese cross to identify their ambulances.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This is especially important in countries such as Australia, where St.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] John Ambulance operate one state and one territory ambulance service, and all of Australia's other ambulance services use variations on a red Maltese cross.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Fire service operated ambulances may display the Cross of St.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Florian (often incorrectly called a Maltese cross) as this cross is frequently used as a fire department logo (St.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Florian being the patron saint of firefighters).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The active visual warnings are usually in the form of flashing lights.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These flash in order to attract the attention of other road users as the ambulance approaches, or to provide warning to motorists approaching a stopped ambulance in a dangerous position on the road.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Common colours for ambulance warning beacons are blue, red, amber, and white (clear).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] However the colours may vary by country and sometimes by operator.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] There are several technologies in use to achieve the flashing effect.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These include flashing a light bulb or LED, flashing or rotating halogen, and strobe lights, which are usually brighter than incandescent lights.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Incandescent and LED lights may also be programmed to burn steadily, without flashing, which is required in some provinces.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These hidden lights may not be apparent until they are activated.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Additionally, some of the standard lights fitted to an ambulance (e.g. headlamps, tail lamps) may be programmed to flash.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Flashing headlights (typically the high beams, flashed alternately) are known as a wig-wag.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Additional white lights may be placed strategically around the vehicle to illuminate the area around it when it is dark, almost always at the rear for loading and unloading stretchers and often at the sides as well.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In areas very far North or South where there are times of year with long periods of darkness, additional driving lights at the front are often fitted as well to increase visibility for the driver.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In order to increase safety, it is best practice to have 360° coverage with the active warnings, improving the chance of the vehicle being seen from all sides.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In some countries, such as the United States, this may be mandatory.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The roof, front grille, sides and rear of the body, and front fenders are common places to mount emergency lights.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] A certain balance must be made when deciding on the number and location of lights: too few and the ambulance may not be noticed easily, too many and it becomes a massive distraction for other road users more than it is already, increasing the risk of local accidents.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In addition to visual warnings, ambulances can be fitted with **audible warnings**, sometimes known as sirens, which can alert people and vehicles to the presence of an ambulance before they can be seen.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The first audible warnings were mechanical bells, mounted to either the front or roof of the ambulance.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Most modern ambulances are now fitted with electronic sirens, producing a range of different noises which ambulance operators can use to attract more attention to themselves, particularly when proceeding through an intersection or in heavy traffic.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The speakers for modern sirens can be integral to the lightbar, or they may be hidden in or flush to the grill to reduce noise inside the ambulance that may interfere with patient care and radio communications.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulances can additionally be fitted with airhorn audible warnings to augment the effectiveness of the siren system, or may be fitted with extremely loud two-tone air horns as their primary siren.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] A recent development is the use of the RDS system of car radios.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The ambulance is fitted with a short range FM transmitter, set to RDS code 31, which interrupts the radio of all cars within range, in the manner of a traffic broadcast, but in such a way that the user of the receiving radio is unable to opt-out of the message (as with traffic broadcasts).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] This feature is built into every RDS radio for use in national emergency broadcast systems, but short-range units on emergency vehicles can prove an effective means of alerting traffic to their presence.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] It is, however, unlikely that this system could replace audible warnings, as it is unable to alert pedestrians, those not using a compatible radio or even have it turned off.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In the United States, the cost of an ambulance ride may be paid for from several sources, and this will depend on the local situation type of service being provided, by whom, and to whom.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] There are differing levels of qualification that the ambulance crew may hold, from holding no formal qualification to having a fully qualified doctor on board.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Most ambulance services require at least two crew members to be on every ambulance (one to drive, and one to attend the patient).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] It may be the case that only the attendant need be qualified, and the driver might have no medical training.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In some locations, an advanced life support ambulance may be crewed by one paramedic and one technician, or in countries like Australia advanced life support registered paramedics.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Military ambulances have historically included vehicles based on civilian designs and at times also included armored, but unarmed, vehicle ambulances based upon armoured personnel carriers (APCs).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In the Second World War vehicles such as the Hanomag Sd Kfz 251 half-track were pressed into service as ad hoc ambulances, and in more recent times purpose-built AFVs such as the U.S.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] M1133 medical evacuation vehicle serve the exclusive purpose of armored medical vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Civilian based designs may be painted in appropriate colors, depending on the operational requirements (i.e. camouflage for field use, white for United Nations peacekeeping, etc.).
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] For example, the British Royal Army Medical Corps has a fleet of white ambulances, based on production trucks.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Military helicopters have also served both as ad hoc and purpose-built air ambulances since they are extremely useful for MEDEVAC.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In terms of equipment, military ambulances are barebones, often being nothing more than a box on wheels with racks to place manual stretchers, though for the operational conditions and level of care involved this is usually sufficient.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Since laws of war demand ambulances be marked with one of the emblems of the Red Cross not to mount offensive weapons, military ambulances are often unarmed.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] It is a generally accepted practice in most countries to classify the personnel attached to military vehicles marked as ambulances as non-combatants; however, this does not always exempt medical personnel from coming under fire – accidental or deliberate.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] As a result, medics and other medical personnel attached to military ambulances are usually put through basic military training, on the assumption that they may have to use a weapon.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The laws of war do allow non-combatant military personnel to carry individual weapons for protecting themselves and casualties.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] However, not all militaries exercise this right to their personnel.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The Israeli Defense Forces modified a number of its Merkava main battle tanks with ambulance features in order to allow rescue operations to take place under heavy fire in urban warfare.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] The modifications were made following a failed rescue attempt in which Palestinian gunmen killed two soldiers who were providing aid for a Palestinian woman in Rafah.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Since M113 armored personnel carriers and regular up-armored ambulances are not sufficiently protected against anti-tank weapons and improvised explosive devices, it was decided to use the heavily armored Merkava tank.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Its rear door enables the evacuation of critically wounded soldiers.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Israel did not remove the Merkava's weaponry, claiming that weapons were more effective protection than emblems since Palestinian militants would disregard any symbols of protection and fire at ambulances anyway.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Some navies operate ocean-going hospital ships to lend medical assistance in high casualty situations such as wars or natural disasters.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] These hospital ships fulfill the criteria of an ambulance (transporting the sick or injured), although the capabilities of a hospital ship are more on par with a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] In line with the laws of war, these ships can display a prominent Red Cross or Red Crescent to confer protection under the appropriate Geneva Convention.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] However, this designation has not always protected hospital ships from enemy fire.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Ambulettes provide patient transport service for non-emergency situations.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Scheduling is a major factor in their effective use.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] When an ambulance is retired, it may be donated or sold to another EMS provider or find their new usage in developing countries.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Alternately, it may be adapted into a storage and transport vehicle for crime scene identification equipment, a command post at community events, or support vehicle, such as a logistics unit.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Others are refurbished and resold, or may just have their emergency equipment removed to be sold to private businesses or individuals, who then can use them as small recreational vehicles.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] They may also have a perfectly serviceable body or vehicle (or both) separated from the other and reused.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Toronto City Council operates a "Caravan of Hope" project to give retired Toronto ambulances a second life by donating them to the people of El Salvador.
[src:dodge-dart/ambulance] Since Ontario laws require ambulances to be retired after just four and a half years in service, the City of Toronto decommissions and auctions around 28 ambulances each year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The **Dodge Dart** is a line of passenger cars produced by Dodge from the 1959 to 1976 model years in North America, with production extended to later years in various other markets.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The production Dodge Dart was introduced as a lower-priced full-size model in 1960 and 1961, but became a mid-size car for one model year for 1962, and was then reduced to a compact for two generations, from 1963 to 1976.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler had first used 'Dart' name plates on two Italian styled show cars, in 1956 and 1957, before it became a Dodge model name.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart nameplate was resurrected for a Fiat-derived compact car that was introduced in 2012.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart name originally appeared on a 1956 Chrysler show car, featuring a streamlined body designed by the Italian coachbuilder Carrozzeria Ghia, that was later modified and renamed the Dart Diablo.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For 1957, Ghia built Chrysler a second, visually similar show car, the Chrysler Ghia Super Dart 400.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The first Dodge Darts were introduced for the 1960 model year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] They were downsized large cars developed to replace Plymouths in the standard, low-priced car segment for the Dodge dealer network.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge dealers had been selling Plymouths since 1930, but divisional restructuring took the Plymouth brand away from the Dodge dealer network.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Project planners proposed the name Dart, only to have Chrysler executives demand an expensive research program that produced the name Zipp.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] This was promptly rejected in favor of Dart.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] With the cancellation of Chrysler's upper level DeSoto brand, upper-level Dodge products were pushed upmarket, while using Plymouth products with more features for lower-level Dodge products.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart sedans and coupes were based on the unibody Plymouth platform with a 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase, shorter than the standard-size Dodge line.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] However, the Dart station wagons used the same 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase as the upmarket Polara wagons.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart line was offered in three trim levels: the basic Seneca, mid-range Pioneer, and premium Phoenix.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The new Dart came standard with a new engine, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-six.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 318 cu in (5.2 L) (standard equipment on certain Phoenix and Pioneer body styles) and 361 cu in (5.9 L) V8s were optional with two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, and with single or dual exhaust.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Sales of the new Dart were greater than those of the full-size Dodge Matador and Dodge Polara, which also created an in-house competitor for Plymouth.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Advertising from 1960 and 1961 compared the Dart to the "C" car (Chevrolet), the "F" car (Ford) and the "P" car (Plymouth).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] After the economic downturn of 1958–59, Dodge production for 1960 rebounded to 367,804 cars, the division's highest total to date, and good for sixth place behind Chevrolet, Ford, Plymouth, Rambler, and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler officials were somewhat less comforted at how 87% of Dodge's volume consisted of the low-profit Dart line, compared to the upmarket Matador and Polara, of which only 41,000 were sold for the 1960 model year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] As the Dart's sales climbed, Plymouth's sales dropped.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler executives did little to stop the infighting between the divisions.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dart sales were so strong in 1960 that production of the medium-priced model lines were reduced.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The full-size, mid-priced Matador was discontinued after the 1960 model year as buyers selected the slightly smaller but better-appointed and less expensive Dart Phoenix.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The premium Polara remained in the medium-price segment in 1961.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For the 1961 model year, the Dart continued as the smallest full-size Dodge.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It retained the 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase, and was restyled to emulate the larger Polara.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The same three trim levels were available: the premium Phoenix, mid-range Pioneer, and base Seneca.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Once again, wagons shared the Polara's 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase; they also shared the Polara's unique side-mounted taillights.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Engine choices included the 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-six, and the 318 cu in (5.2 L) and 361 cu in (5.9 L) V8s were also available in various configurations.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Phoenix convertibles were equipped with V8 engines.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Beginning mid-year, some Darts ordered with the 225 engine were equipped with the die-cast aluminum block.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Darts in all series were equipped as standard with three-speed, column-shifted manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's pushbutton-shifted TorqueFlite automatic was available at extra cost.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The alternator, introduced as standard equipment in 1960 on the Valiant, replaced the previous DC generator on all 1961 Chrysler products.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Canadian-built 1961 Darts were identical to U.S. models on the outside, but the interior trim, controls, and displays were those used on the U.S.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Virgil Exner's 1961 styling with its reverse fins, rear fender scalloping (the taillights were widely referred to as "ingrown toenails"), and the concave grille was highly unpopular with consumers.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The low position and small size of the Dart's tail lights, just above the corners of the bumper, was also criticized and drivers of following cars complained that they could not see them.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The wraparound taillights projected light sideward, not rearward.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] By mid-year, Dodge made auxiliary taillights available at extra cost through its dealer network.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] However, these large round lights were mounted near the inboard side of the reverse fins and aggravated the already awkward styling.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1961 automobile market was generally an off-year for automobile sales, and Dodge production went down to 269,367 units, of which 142,708 were Darts.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Among all the Darts sold, almost half (66,100) were the Seneca line, down from 111,600 in 1960.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Combined sales of Dart and Polara were lower than Plymouth's sales for 1961.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge ranked ninth in sales in the American market in 1961, down from sixth place in 1960.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Sales of the compact Dodge Lancer were 74,773 units compared to its Plymouth twin, the Valiant, which sold 143,078 units for the same year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1961 model year saw Dodge's total production drop below the slow-selling 1959 model year and almost the disastrous recession year of 1958 when Dodge faced the consequences of the poor reputation of its 1957 models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dodge Polara 500 was dimensionally identical but not officially a Dart by dint of its different name, and it was not built nor sold in Canada.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart models were the same in Canada as in the U.S. except that the base model was badged *Dart 220*.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart and Polara were downsized as part of Chrysler's hasty effort to compete with what company leaders thought would be downsized large cars from Chevrolet.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] However, they had overheard talk not of the big Chevrolets, but of the compact Chevy II Nova.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] This was a basic front-engine compact to compete more directly than the Corvair with the Ford Falcon, Rambler American, and Plymouth Valiant.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chevrolet's Impala and Ford's Galaxie both remained sized in accord with the prevailing norms of full-size cars.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The redesigned Dart was perceived more as an intermediate, like the Rambler Classic or the Ford Fairlane.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] When Dodge dealers voiced their displeasure at having no true full-size car to offer, Chrysler quickly created the Dodge Custom 880 in January 1962 by putting the 1961 Dodge Polara front end assembly on a version of the 1962 Chrysler Newport body.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1962 Dart, like the Plymouth, was on a new lightweight unibody "B" platform, featuring Chrysler's well-received "Torsion-Aire" torsion bar front suspension and asymmetric rear leaf springs.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1961, a third-generation turbine engine (CR2A) was installed in a 1962 Dart, which successfully drove from New York City to Los Angeles, through snowstorms, rain and heavy winds.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart's new B-body chassis platform was quite long-lived; while 1962 was the only year for a B-body model named "Dart", the B platform remained in use with only very slight modification and a few new letter designations through to the 1981 R-body cars.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For 1963, Dodge made a last-minute decision to drop the Lancer name in favor of *Dart* for Dodge's newly designed "senior compact", a marketing term referring to the wheelbase having grown to 111 in (2,819 mm) from the Lancer's 106.5 in (2,705 mm).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The longer wheelbase gave more rear seat legroom than the previous Lancer or the contemporaneous Valiant.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was available as a 2- or 4-door sedan, a 2-door hardtop coupe, a station wagon, and a convertible.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Three trim levels were offered: the low-spec *170*, the high-spec *270*, and the premium *GT*, which was available only as a 2-door hardtop or convertible.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1963 Dart has a turning diameter of 38.9 ft (11.9 m).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was an instant market success, with 1963 sales up sharply compared to those of the 1962 Lancer.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart remained extremely popular through the end of the Dart's production run in 1976 in comparison to the Ford Falcon and the Chevrolet Nova.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Initial engine offerings were two sizes of the slant-six: a 170 cu in (2.8 L), 101 hp (75 kW) version was fitted as standard equipment, and a 225 cu in (3.7 L), 145 hp (108 kW) version was available for less than $50 extra.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The aluminum engine block for the 225 was discontinued early in the 1963 model year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] After the start of the 1964 model year, an all-new, compact, lightweight 273 cu in (4.5 L) LA V8 producing 180 bhp (130 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor was introduced as the top engine option.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] 1964 was the last year for pushbutton control of the optional Torqueflite automatic transmission, so 1963 and 1964 models were the only compact Darts so equipped.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Standard axle ratios in 1964 were 2.93:1 with automatic transmission and 225 engine, or 3.23:1 with manual transmission and 225 engine, or with 170 engine and either transmission.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] New features included stronger door locks and a refined automatic choke.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1965, the 2-barrel 273 remained available, but a new performance version of the 273 engine was released with a 4-barrel carburetor, 10.5:1 compression, a more aggressive camshaft with solid tappets, and other upgrades which increased output to 235 bhp (175 kW).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] At the same time, the Dodge Dart Charger was offered.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Chargers were yellow Dart GT hardtops with black interiors, Charger 273 engines, (Plymouth called their 4 barrel 273 Commando), premium mechanical and trim specifications, and special "Charger" badging.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] They were the first Dodge models to bear the "Charger" name.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The following year the larger B-body Dodge Charger was introduced, and the "Charger" name was thenceforth associated with Dart models only in the "Charger 225" marketing name for the optional larger 6-cylinder engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Other new options for 1965 included upgraded suspension components and larger 14 in (356 mm) wheels and tires.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Factory-installed air conditioning became available after the start of the 1965 model year, as well as disc brakes, which required the 14 in (356 mm) wheels to clear the calipers.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For North American domestic-market vehicles, the base 170 engine was replaced for 1970 with a stronger new 198 cu in (3.2 L) version of the slant-6.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] This new base engine was also less costly to make, for unlike the previous 170 engine, the 198 used the same block as the 225.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The smaller displacement was achieved with a new crankshaft (3.64 in (92 mm) stroke vs. the 4.125 in (104.8 mm) stroke of the 225 crank) and connecting rods (7.006 in (178.0 mm) long vs. the 6.67 in (169 mm) rods in the 225).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Nevertheless, the 225 remained an upgrade option.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 2-barrel 273 cu in (4.5 L) small-block V8 was supplanted on the option list in 1968 by a 318 cu in (5.2 L) 2-barrel engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] At the same time the 4-barrel carbureted 273 235 bhp (175 kW) was replaced on the options list by the 275 bhp (205 kW) 4-barrel carbureted 340 cu in (5.6 L) available only in the 1968–1972 Swinger and the hottest Dart, the performance-oriented GTS models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart GTS came standard with the 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart and its sister model—the Plymouth Valiant—were substantially redesigned for the 1967 model year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In addition to new styling, the cars received revised steering systems, wider front track and frame rail spacing, and redesigned K-members capable of accepting larger engines.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart kept this basic form, with facelifts consisting of revised front and rear-end styling and interior trim, until the end of A-body production in 1976 for North America and 1981 for South America.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The restyled Dart for 1967 featured a rear window with compound inverse curves.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] This created a unique appearance at the rear of the greenhouse, but tended to collect snow and created thick C-pillars that looked formal but created blind spots for drivers.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Curved side glass was used for the first time on a Chrysler compact.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The front featured a new dual-plane front end contour: the center section of the grille, bumper, and leading edge of the hood were recessed from the front plane of the car.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The single headlamps were placed forward of the recessed center section, defining the front plane.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Park/turn lamps were set into the grille, in the corners formed by the transition area between the recessed and forward sections.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] With the new design, changes were made to the Dart lineup, beginning with the elimination of its station wagons and the base model's "170" designation.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The only body styles were the 2- and 4-door sedans, the hardtop, and the convertible.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The base 170 model was now badged simply as "Dart".
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 270 and GT versions carried on unchanged for the most part.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In late 1967, the GTS model debuted but was built in limited quantities due to its lateness in the model year; the 1968 GTS was, arguably, improved by fitting the new high-output 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1967 Dart, along with all other 1967 Chrysler products, got a new dual-circuit brake hydraulic system to ensure a loss of pressure in the front brakes would not prevent the rear brakes from working, and vice versa.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The system also incorporated a brake system fault telltale on the dashboard.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Other changes to comply with new federal safety laws included collapsible steering columns, additional padding on the dashboard and sun visors.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder belt anchors were also provided for front outboard occupants.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1967 redesign removed all traces of the older Virgil Exner styling that proved less popular by the early 1960s.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The newer body was trimmer and proved extremely popular, causing sales of the Dart to surpass compacts from Ford and GM.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Changes for 1968 were relatively subtle.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The park and turn lights in the grille were moved slightly inboard and made round.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Side marker lights were added to the front fenders and rear quarter panels, to comply with newly introduced Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 108.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder harnesses (separate, this year and until 1973, from the lap belts) and non-glare matte finish on the windshield wiper arms were also part of the 1968 federally mandated safety package.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's "clean air package" emission control system became standard equipment on cars sold in all 50 states.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The steering linkage was revised again, as were the windshield and rear window gaskets and trim-lock strips, leaving the 1967 pieces as one-year-only items.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The standard rear axle ratio was dropped from 2.93 to 2.76 with all standard-performance engines and automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Part-throttle downshift functionality was added as a refinement to the TorqueFlite automatic transmission in 6-cylinder cars, to retain acceptable city performance with the taller rear axle ratio.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A limited option for 1968 only, code L023, the Hurst-reworked Hemi Darts used the 426 cu in (7.0 L) Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] These special models (only 80 were made) were created strictly for drag racing, and included a non-warranty disclaimer.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] On February 20, 1968, corporate headquarters in Highland Park, Michigan, sent out a press release to Dodge dealerships.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was a promotional pitch purposed at selling drag-ready, Hemi-powered Darts.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The press release stated that Dodge wanted to make a factory-built and ready drag racer out of the 68 Dart GTS hardtop for competition in class B Super Stock (drag racing).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Engineers stated the new Hemi Dart reached speeds of 130 mph (209 km/h) in less than 11 seconds and 1⁄4 mi (402 m) times in the 10-11 second range, although times have been reported as low as the 9-10 second range.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] To keep weight low, a fiberglass hood and fenders were used.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The hood featured a functional intake scoop and four hood pins for full lift-off removal of the hood.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Lightweight acid-dipped steel doors with thin side window glass were used.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] As the doors lacked a window mechanism, a strap was attached to the bottom of the glass on the interior door panel.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] To keep glass up, the strap latched to the inside of the door.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The interior included only two bucket seats from a Dodge van.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The center console, heater, sound deadeners, side-view mirrors, radio, carpeting, and even armrests were omitted to save weight.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A high-performance Mopar battery was moved to the trunk to free up room and improve weight distribution.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Darts could be ordered with either a four-speed manual or three-speed automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Manual transmission equipped cars, code A-833, featured a Dana 60 built heavy-duty axle with a 4.88 gear ratio, heavy-duty clutch, steel bellhousing, and special torque shaft and pivots.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Manual transmissions were modified by removing synchronizers which lowered the chances of missed shifts.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A Hurst floor-mounted shifter came standard.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The automatic transmissions were the then-new Chrysler-built 727 TorqueFlite three-speed with 8-3/4 inch large stem pinion center section with a 4.86 gear set, and a 2,600 rpm high speed torque converter.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] They were also modified with a floor-mounted Hurst shifter for manual shifting.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Other features include heavy-duty rear shocks, heavy-duty radiator with a seven-blade fan, and deep groove pulleys, a high capacity oil pump, solid-lifter cam, and a roller timing chain to reduce stretch and provide more reliable performance.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A transistorized dual points breaker distributor coupled with a Prestolite ignition and solid core wires were also used.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The cars weighed approximately 3,000 lb (1,361 kg).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The cars were designed to meet street legal requirements, but due to the modifications, the cars came with disclaimers that they were not for street use, but rather "supervised acceleration trials", or drag racing.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 2-door sedan was dropped at the end of 1968 and replaced with the Swinger 2-door hardtop for 1969 available in Custom, GT, and GTS trim.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The entire 1969 Dart range received trim updates including another minor revision of the grille and a return to rectangular park/turn lights.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1968 round side marker lights were replaced with rectangular reflectors.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Head restraints were optional equipment until January 1, 1969, when their installation became mandatory under federal law.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 6-cylinder models received a carburetor anti-ice system borrowed from Canadian-market Chrysler 6-cylinder engines, and the drum brake automatic adjusters were revised for more consistent operation.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] At the top of the Dart performance range for 1969, there was limited availability of the 440 V8 in the Dart GTS model.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was refreshed for 1970 with front and rear changes designed to bring the car closer to the design themes found in Dodge's full-size vehicles through grille and contour changes.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In the rear, the Dart's new rectangular tail lights were set into a wedge-shaped rear bumper design continuing the angled trailing edge of the new deck lid and quarter panels.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The revised rear styling did not change the 14.1 cubic ft trunk space of the 1969 model.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] 14-inch wheels became standard equipment, and the 170 cu in (2.8 L) slant-6 was replaced by a larger 198 cu in (3.2 L) version for improved base-model performance and greater manufacturing economy—the 198 used the same block as the 225, while the 170 had used a different block.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Changes to the fuel system improved drivability, economy, and emission control.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Part-throttle downshift was added to the 8-cylinder automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In compliance with FMVSS 108, side marker lights and reflectors were installed at all four corners.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] 1970 Darts for the US and Canadian markets were built in Canada at the Windsor, Ontario, or Los Angeles, California assembly plant.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] All 1970 Darts got the federally mandated steering column and ignition lock.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The "Swinger" name was applied to all the Dart two-door hardtops except in the high-line custom series.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Other changes were made to the Dart line to avoid internal competition with Dodge's new Challenger: the Dart convertible was discontinued along with the optional 383 cu in (6.3 L) V8, leaving the 275 bhp (205 kW) 340 4-barrel V8 as the top Dart engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The performance model in the Dart line for 1970 was the Swinger 340 2-door hardtop.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1970 Swinger 340 came with functional hood scoops with 340 emblems.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Standard equipment included front disc brakes (only on the Swinger), heavy-duty "Rallye" suspension, a 3.23:1 rear axle ratio, fiberglass-belted bias-ply tires mounted to 14 × 5½ inch steel wheels, and a bumblebee stripe.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Optional equipment included an upgrade over the standard bench seat with all-vinyl bucket seats, with which a center console could be ordered.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A performance hood upgrade with scoops was painted flat black with hood tie-down pins.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Mechanical options included power-assisted brakes and steering.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Rallye wheels and wire wheel covers were also optional, as was a 6000 rpm tachometer and a vinyl roof covering in black or white.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For 1971, Chrysler introduced a 2-door hardtop in the Valiant line called the Scamp.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was the same car as the Swinger with a Valiant front clip.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1970 Dart's dual tail lamps were given over to the badge-engineered Scamp, while the 1971 Dart received new smaller quad taillamps that would be used through 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The custom 2-door hardtop coupe became the Swinger, and the standard Swinger became the Swinger Special.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge gained a version of Plymouth's popular Valiant-based fastback Duster which was to be named the *Beaver*, but when Chrysler's marketing department learned that "beaver" was CB slang for vagina, the vehicle was renamed the "Dart Demon".
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] As was the case with previous Dodge rebadges of Plymouth Valiants, such as the 1961–1962 Lancer, sales of the Demon lagged behind those of the Duster.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] With optional hood scoops and blackout hood treatment, the car was advertised as a performance car.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon's Dart-type front fender wheel lips and Duster-type rear wheel fender lips reveal the car was essentially a Duster with Dart front sheet metal and other minor styling changes.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A new audio option became available for 1971: Chrysler's cassette-recorder.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Unlike the 8-track tapes, the cassette player was relatively compact, and it was mounted on the console or on its own floor-mount casing.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] This unit offered an available microphone in which one could record their own dictation.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Swinger 340, Dart's performance model, was replaced by the Demon 340, 275 HP engine with an optional 4-speed manual transmission, optional hood scoops, and blackout hood treatment.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1971, Chrysler ended their longstanding corporate practice of installing left-hand-threaded wheel studs on the left side of the vehicle; all-wheel studs on the Dart thenceforth used conventional right-hand threads.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon had new fender-mounted metal "Demon" badges without the small devil character on the 1971 decals.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The "Demon" decal on the rear of the car was replaced by *Dodge* and *Dart* emblems on the lower right edge of the deck lid.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Some Demons with the side and rear panel tape stripes retained the tape devil character.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A new, optional, single, hood scoop replaced 1971's dual scoops, and was coupled with a hood-paint blackout that had been standard on the 1971 high-trim/high-value Demon Sizzler model.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Cars equipped with the optional rally wheels now came with newly restyled center caps, finished in a light-argent (silver) paint.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Demon production was substantially less than the Duster's; this is reflected in higher collector car values for the Demon, especially V8 models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1973 model year Darts received new front styling with revised fenders, grille, header panel, and hood.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Impact absorbing front bumpers were installed to comply with new federal regulations, as well as side-impact guard beams in the doors and new emission control devices.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] New single-piston disc brakes replaced the more complex 4-piston units offered from 1965 to 1972.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's new electronic ignition system was standard equipment on all engines, and starter motors were revised for faster engine cranking.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The K-frame was modified to accommodate a new spool-type engine mount that limited engine roll to 3°.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The upper ball joints were upgraded to the larger B-body units.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Along with these chassis changes, the wheel bolt pattern on Darts with disc brakes was enlarged from 4 in (101.6 mm) to the 4.5 in (114.3 mm) pattern common to the larger B- and C-body Chrysler-built passenger cars.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Darts with 4-wheel drum brakes continued with the smaller bolt pattern.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The standard rear axle was still the 7¼-inch unit, but the heavy-duty option was now an 8¼-inch item rather than the previous 8¾-inch rear axle.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Standard rear axle ratios were 2.76:1 with automatic transmission and 3.23:1 with manual, though other ratios were available.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Vent wings were deleted from the Swinger but not from the 4-door sedans.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A new "Quiet Car" package was available, consisting of extra sound insulation, premium exhaust hangers, and an exhaust resonator.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon fastback was renamed "Dart Sport" in response to poor sales.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was thought that the "Demon" name and devil-with-pitchfork logo negatively affected sales to people of faith.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The high-performance model thus became Dart Sport 340, and 1973 saw styling changes to go along with the name change.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport received the same new front end as the other Darts, and its taillights were changed to two lights per side, each with a chrome trim ring.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] These would remain unchanged through the 1976 model year.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1974, the US federal 5 mph (8.0 km/h) bumper impact standards were expanded to cover rear bumpers as well as front ones, and as a result, the Swinger and Dart sedan's rear bumpers grew much more massive.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Taillights larger than the previous year's items were set above the rear bumper, rather than within it.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder and lap belts were finally combined in all Chrysler products into a retractable, inertia-sensitive, single-buckle design Chrysler called "Unibelt", replacing the difficult-to-use separate lap and shoulder belts that had been installed through 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Arab oil embargo of 1973, increased sales of smaller cars in the U.S.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge introduced the Dart SE (special edition) in mid-1974 as a four-door sedan and two-door hardtop.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The SE included velour high back bucket seats with folding armrest, carpeted door panels, woodgrain instrument panel, and deluxe wheel covers along with a TorqueFlite automatic transmission as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The SE came equipped with the "quiet car" package introduced in 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The air conditioning system available on all Darts had increased capacity, quicker cooldown and lower minimum temperatures.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] An evaporator pressure regulator valve, long used on larger Chrysler products, varied the compressor's capacity without cycling the clutch.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport 340 was replaced by the Dart Sport 360 245 Bhp. as the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engine replaced the 340 cu in (5.6 L) engine discontinued after 1973.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 1975 models were virtually identical to the 1974s, except for a new grille and that California and some high-altitude models were equipped with catalytic converters and so required unleaded gasoline.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] All 1975 models were required to pass a roof crush test and to meet this stringent requirement, additional reinforcements were added to all Dart 2-door hardtops.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Heavy gauge steel in the windshield pillar area had been incorporated into the windshield, pillar, and roof design.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Darts were also equipped with an improved energy-absorbing steering column which used multiple slots in the column jacket to replace prior used convoluted mesh design.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] At impact, force applied to the steering wheel curled the column jacket back over a mandrel mounted on the floor.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Federal Motor Safety Standards briefly required that the front seat belts include a starter interlock system that prevented the engine from starting unless the front seat outboard occupant and the driver fastened their belts.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 198 slant-six engine was discontinued and the 225 became standard equipment on all models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] As in 1974, the 360 V8 was limited to the Dart Sport 360 model.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A 4-speed manual transmission was offered with the 6-cylinder engine for the first time in the North American market since 1965 and with a new 30% overdrive 4th gear ratio.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was Chrysler's first application of overdrive since 1959.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The final drive ratio in fourth gear was 2.36:1 on the slant-six cars equipped with 3.23:1 rear axle, and 2.15:1 on the V8s equipped with 2.94:1 rear axle.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The result was less engine noise and wear and greater fuel economy.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Also for 1975, heaters had 14% more heating capacity than in the previous year's models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The added capacity was the result of adding a third speed to the blower system, which provided 20% greater airflow at maximum setting.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The electrically heated backglass defogger grid timer cycle was doubled to 10 minutes.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Additionally, sound insulation was improved.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] 1976 was the Dart's final year in the North-American market.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The rear-view mirror was mounted on the windshield rather than from the roof.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The grille's parking lamps were cast in amber, whereas the previous years had clear lenses with amber-colored bulbs.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport 360 was dropped as a separate model in 1976, but the 360 cu in (5.9 L) four-barrel, dual exhaust (without catalytic converters) V8 was a $376 option (except in California) for the $3,370 Dart Sport V8 models with automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] *Car & Driver* magazine tested the Dart Sport 360 in the April 1976 issue, pitting it against the Chevrolet Corvette and Pontiac Trans Am, and found its top speed of 121.6 mph (195.7 km/h) to be second to the Corvette's 124.5 mph (200.4 km/h).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dart Custom 4-Door Sedan was dropped as the mid-level 4-door sedan model, but the features and trim were carried over as option package A68.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Sedans equipped with the Custom package received the same "Custom" front fender badges as were applied to the standalone 1975 models of the same name.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Elimination of the Custom series narrowed Dart's 4-Door Sedan offerings in Dart's final year to two models, Dart and Dart Special Edition.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1976, the Dart was offered with a police package, with production code A38.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The A38 Dart had high-specification components and systems throughout, including a heavy-duty suspension with a rear sway bar, stronger leaf springs and firmer shock absorbers, larger brakes with semi-metallic front disc pads, maximum engine cooling as well as a high-capacity alternator and battery.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The engines were Chrysler's 225 slant-six, 318 V8, and 360 cu in (5.9 L) LA V8 (220 H.P., with non-catalyst in 49-state models and a true dual exhaust; California models had a single exhaust with the catalytic converter) with an A727 TorqueFlite transmission.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Police-specific equipment such as a calibrated speedometer ("certified" 120 mph), high-intensity dome light and wiring harness for a rooftop light bar were standard equipment with an A-pillar spotlight and push bars were optional.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Production volume was low, with most A38 Darts going to the Los Angeles and Ventura police departments in Southern California.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For the most part, police agencies preferred the larger intermediate Dodge Coronet or full-size Dodge Monaco.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] For 1973 and 1974, the **Convertriple** option on the Dart Sport included a fold-down rear seat/security panel offering 6 ft 5 in (1.96 m) of lengthwise space, and a manually operated metal sunroof.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was advertised as "three cars in one": an economy compact, a convertible alternative because of the sunroof, and a roomy station wagon alternative because of the fold down rear seat.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Convertriple was the basis for the 1975 **Hang 10** option.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] It was aimed at surfers in an attempt by Dodge marketers to better determine consumer preferences in a declining performance market.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Hang ten is a surfing expression for balancing at the end of a surfboard with ten toes over the nose of the board while riding the wave.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Available only in eggshell white exterior with a factory-installed sunroof, the car's fold-down rear seat permitted the loading of a surfboard through the trunk.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Hang 10 option continued the surfing theme with various colored stripe material accenting the white vinyl seats and door panels.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Orange shag carpet covered the back of the fold-down rear seat while the dash and center console had orange accents.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Red and blue exterior stripes started at the quarter panels with a wave-riding surfer graphic.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] A surfboard design ran down the center of the hood.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In mid-1974, Dodge introduced the **Caravan Tan** trim package.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Features for this Dart Sport included a desert-hued vinyl bench seat with multi-colored striped inserts and white piping, and gold-colored instrument panel, dashboard, and carpeting.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Exterior color choices were dark moonstone, Sienna, gold metallic, dark gold metallic, golden fawn, and white.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In a tie-in with the United States Bicentennial, a **Spirit of '76** edition of the Dart Sport featured white paint with prominent red and blue bodyside striping meant to evoke the image of the American flag.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In response to increased interest in fuel economy, Dodge offered the **Dart Lite** fuel economy package which weighed at least 150 lb (68 kg) less than the ordinary Dart Sport.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The 225 slant-six was the only available engine, equipped with an aluminum intake manifold for the first time since 1960 and a specially calibrated carburetor and distributor.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Bumper reinforcement brackets were aluminum instead of steel, while the hood and trunk lid bracing and inner panels were also aluminum.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The slant-six engine block had already been modified for reduced weight in 1975; in the middle of 1976 production, its crankshaft was changed from forged steel to lighter cast iron.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The high-flow exhaust system included a dual-biscuit catalytic converter, a larger 2¼" headpipe, and the muffler used on V8 models.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Lite was equipped with a 2.94:1 rear axle rather than the customary 3.21:1 ratio when the car was ordered with a three- or four-speed manual transmission.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The A833OD Overdrive 4-speed manual transmission housing was made of aluminum and had a .73:1 final drive ratio which allowed cruising at highway speeds with minimum engine revolutions.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Like all other Darts, the Dart Lites with automatic transmission came with a 2.76:1 rear axle as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Lite with manual transmission was rated by the EPA at 36 mpg (6.5 L/100km) in highway driving.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Darts were offered to the taxicab industry for their whole production run from 1963 to 1976.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Mechanically, Dart taxicabs were generally equipped with heavy-duty brakes, tires, shock absorbers, front torsion bars and rear leaf springs, a high-output alternator, an increased-capacity cooling system, and extra-lean carburetor calibration for greater economy.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1976, the Chrome Yellow taxi package was available only with a 225 slant-six engine producing 95 hp (71 kW) and 170 lb⋅ft (230 N⋅m); transmission was the (rare) A-727-RG (raised-deck motor, which was the slant-six series) with California emissions, 90 hp (67 kW) and 165 lb⋅ft (224 N⋅m).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Options included a radio suppression package and a Fuel Pacer System.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Many—if not all—of them had a body-color paint sales code of "999", meaning special order paint.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge offered a performance version of the Dart GT in 1966.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Known as the D-Dart for competitive use in NHRA's D/stock class, the 273 V8 was modified to produce 275 bhp (205 kW).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Most of the power came from a larger carburetor and a more radical camshaft.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The bulletin sent to the dealers from Chrysler also mentions an 8.75 in (222 mm) rear axle with 4.89:1 final drive ratio.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1966, the SCCA introduced the new Trans-American Sedan Championship that allowed competition among Dodge Darts, Plymouth Barracudas, Chevrolet Corvairs, Ford Mustangs, and other "production touring cars" with a maximum wheelbase of 116 in (2,946.4 mm).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The cars competed in two classes, over 2 liters and under 2 liters.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Few modifications were allowed; bumpers, rear seats, and floor mats could be removed, mufflers could be replaced with straight pipes, and different wheels could be used so long as the stock rim diameter and width were maintained.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Any engine component available over the dealer parts counter was sanctioned for use.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Bob Tullius' race team, called "Group 44," used Dart 270 model coupes and GT coupes with 273-4bbl engines and were sponsored by Quaker State.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] The team won the 24-hour endurance race at Marlboro Motor Raceway in car No.4 driven by Tullius and Tony Adamowicz, who would also go on to win at Riverside International Raceway.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge pulled sponsorship of the Darts after one season.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] Although racers like Dick Landy and Don Garlits had modified Darts in the mid-1960s to run in the National Hot Rod Association - NHRA funny car class using the 426 Hemi, super stock class racing of the Dart was almost non-existent due to the small V-8s available.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] In 1968, Dodge contracted Hurst Performance to build a limited number of Darts powered by the 440 cu in (7.2 L) RB big-block and 426 cu in (7.0 L) Hemi-powered Darts to compete in the SS/B class as the LO23 "Hurst Hemi Dart".
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p01] According to Chrysler staff engineer Larry Shepard, the majority of these Darts were Hemi powered, although a small pilot run of fifty 440-powered Darts were also built in 1968.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Right-hand drive 1960, 1961, and 1962 Darts were exported to Commonwealth countries such as Australia, New Zealand, South Africa, and Singapore.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] In Australia they were badged as the Dodge Phoenix.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] In South Africa, a DeSoto-branded version of the car called the Diplomat was sold from 1960 to 1962, as well.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Once the "Dart" name was moved to Dodge's compact car for 1963, the Phoenix was no longer Dart-related; each year thereafter through 1971, the "Phoenix" name was applied to the RHD version of a Dodge or Plymouth B-body or C-body for Commonwealth export.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Chrysler Australia used the 1967 Dart front end in the Australian-built VE Valiant.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The two-door coupe versions of the subsequent VF and VG models used the Dart two-door's body from the A-pillar back married to an Australian front end.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Australian sedan and pickup truck models were also exported in knock-down kit form to New Zealand for local assembly there from 1963 to 1978.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Dodge Darts were assembled in right-hand drive in South Africa during the 1960s and up until 1972 and sold locally as the Chrysler Valiant.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] All South African models were built with a locally sourced 225 cu in six-cylinder engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Plymouth/Dodge models were fully replaced by Australian Chrysler products from 1972.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Dodge Dart started being produced in Brazil from knock-down kits in October 1969, replacing the Simca-derived Chrysler Esplanada.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Production of A-body Darts continued in Brazil, where they were also sold as Charger, Magnum and Le Baron, through 1981 and in Colombia through 1977.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Dart-based A-body cars with various names including Valiant, Coronado and Polara were produced in Argentina through 1979.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Brazilian A-body cars used the 111-inch wheelbase (2,820 mm) bodystyle from 1970 and were always equipped with the 318 cubic inch V8, set up to run on the lower-octane fuel used in Latin America at the time.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Originally a three-speed manual transmission was standard, with an optional Torqueflite automatic transmission, and later a four-speed manual was also available.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The equipment levels in Brazil were: Sedan de Luxo, Coupe de Luxo, SE, Gran Sedan, Gran Coupe, Charget LS, Le Baron and Magnum with the sporty Charger R/T .
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The last true A-body Dart was built in the summer of 1981 in Brazil.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] This car is virtually identical to the U.S. market's 1976 Swinger.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] From 1965 to 1970 a Spanish version of the Dodge Dart based on the original from the United States was manufactured in the Barreiros Villaverde factory in Madrid.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] In 1969, the Barreiros-made Dart was facelifted with a different front fascia; using the same headlights from Dodge C-38 trucks.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] In March 1971 a new version, using the same 111 in (2,819 mm) wheelbase but with different sheet metal, the Dodge 3700 was produced until 1977 when the Spanish automotive taxation system was changed.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The 3700 actually received the sheet metal from the Argentinian Dodge Polara, with certain modifications for the Spanish market.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The rear wheel openings were larger and round, the grille and all lights were different, as was the instrumentation.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The 3700 also came as standard with front disc brakes and power steering.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] A total of 17,589 units were manufactured of the earlier range (1965 to 1970) in Spain, they were produced as a SKD due to the protectionist Spanish regulations of those years.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] 9,959 Dodge 3700s were built until 1977, although the last new 3700 was only first registered in 1980.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Dart and the 3700 were the biggest national production car available in Spain during all production years.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] It was an expensive luxury car with very low fuel economy by Spanish standards.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Nonetheless, it was considered an economic car for its size in those few markets to which it was exported.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] In Switzerland, for instance, it was priced exactly the same as a V8-engined American-built four-door Dodge Dart Custom and had only slightly less power, but was taxed considerably less.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] These vehicles were also exported to other European markets such as France and the United Kingdom but without much success.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Spanish Dodges never met sales goals and was an expensive failure for the Barreiros concern.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The break-even point was 5,000 cars per year, a goal which was only surpassed once, in 1966.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Barreiros brothers were forced to sell off the company which was reorganized as Chrysler España, S.A.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Dodge Dart GL was a luxury model, while the GT was the sporty version.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The base version has a three-speed manual transmission, while the GT came with either a four-speed manual or a three-speed automatic - this was the same unit as the one mounted in the Chrysler 2 L.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The gasoline Darts had the biggest engine ever mounted into a mass-produced car in Spain, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Chrysler slant-six engine.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The "3700" number is a reference to the 3.7 litres of displacement.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] No other six-cylinder engine car has been produced as much in Spain.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] A diesel Dart (named "Barreiros diesel") was also produced.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] These models, mainly intended for taxi use, were very basic and very slow.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] They have 7-inch round headlamps rather than the large oblong units on fancier Spanish Darts, and use the round taillights from the first generation Simca 1000.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The engine was the Barreiros C65, a 2,007 cc (122.5 cu in) inline-four with 65 PS (48 kW) at 4,500 rpm.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Top speed was claimed to be 124 km/h (77 mph).
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Production of Spanish Dodges stopped in 1977.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Peugeot bought the Villaverde factory, as Chrysler was divesting their European operations in Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Spanish Dodges were popular with members of the Spanish government during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco was killed on 20 December 1973 while traveling in his Dodge 3700 GT.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] On 12 June 1975, Fernando Herrero Tejedor, the Minister Secretary General of the Movimiento Nacional and the politician mentoring Adolfo Suárez, died in a car accident while travelling in his official Dodge 3700 in the municipality of Adanero.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Peugeot would not market another large car in Spain similar to the size of the Dart (the previous Chrysler 180 was smaller) until the Talbot Tagora came out in 1980, albeit without much success.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] Although being the only large Dodge produced locally in Spain, previous American models such as the Coronet and Meadowbrook were exported to Spain ever since the 1950s with moderate success.
[src:dodge-dart/dodge-dart-p02] The Dart name (rather than Aspen) was applied to Dodge-branded F-body cars in Mexico, corresponding to the Mexican Chrysler-branded F-body cars badged as Valiant Volare (without the "é" in the "Volare" nameplate).
